{"id": 29190, "date": "1987-04-14T11:00:00", "date_gmt": "1987-04-14T18:00:00", "guid": {"rendered": "https://estreetshuffle.com/?p=29190"}, "modified": "2026-06-10T15:09:37", "modified_gmt": "2026-06-10T22:09:37", "slug": "matr-bruce-springsteen-nils-lofgren-and-soozie-tyrell-its-all-over-now", "status": "publish", "type": "post", "link": "https://estreetshuffle.com/index.php/1987/04/14/matr-bruce-springsteen-nils-lofgren-and-soozie-tyrell-its-all-over-now/", "title": {"rendered": "It&#8217;s All Over Now"}, "content": {"rendered": "<p>It&#8217;s a Rolling Stones double-shot!</p>\n<p>Yesterday, we took a look at &#8220;Jumpin&#8217; Jack Flash,&#8221; a song Bruce covered three times in unusual circumstances. Today, we take a look at the Stones&#8217; first U.K. #1 hit&#8211;a song Bruce covered twice as many times, in circumstances just as varied.</p>\n<p>&#8220;It&#8217;s All Over Now&#8221; was actually a cover when The Stones covered it in 1964. The Valentinos (featuring the song&#8217;s co-author Bobby Womack) first recorded and released it the year prior.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" class=\"youtube-player\" width=\"758\" height=\"427\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/71XrZ7ghpZg?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" style=\"border:0;\" sandbox=\"allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox\"></iframe></span></div>\n<p>The Stones&#8217; arrangement quickly became the definitive version of the song when it topped the U.K. charts the year of its release. (It only reached #26 in the U.S.)</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" class=\"youtube-player\" width=\"758\" height=\"427\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/Ur-yMil88fU?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" style=\"border:0;\" sandbox=\"allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox\"></iframe></span></div>\n<p>Bruce covered &#8220;It&#8217;s All Over Now&#8221; quite early, first performing it at The Stone Pony with house band Cats on a Smooth Surface in 1983. No one thought to capture that debut performance for posterity, however.</p>\n<p>Its next appearance came more than sixteen years later at a private concert for the high bidders of a charity auction. Bruce performed &#8220;It&#8217;s All Over Now&#8221; that night with Patti Scialfa, Southside Johnny, and Jon Bon Jovi, but if someone recorded it, it stays safely locked away to date.</p>\n<p>The third time was the charm, though. At a Nils Lofgren concert at the Stone Pony during the summer of 2001, Bruce joined Nils on stage for a duet treatment of the Stones&#8217; early classic. This time, it was captured on tape.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" class=\"youtube-player\" width=\"758\" height=\"427\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/Pkz_f0pPJCY?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" style=\"border:0;\" sandbox=\"allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox\"></iframe></span></div>\n<p>The Stone Pony was the scene of Bruce&#8217;s next captured performance, too&#8211;this time with lead vocals by Soozie Tyrell, the guest of honor at her <em>White Lines</em> record release party at in May 2003.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" class=\"youtube-player\" width=\"758\" height=\"427\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/J_Q803Ov1QE?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent&#038;listType=playlist&#038;list=PLnbVaK2f4rahG0FUeHpPvV4kAosh4BFWT\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" style=\"border:0;\" sandbox=\"allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox\"></iframe></span></div>\n<p>But it wasn&#8217;t until the very end of the Magic Tour in 2008 that Bruce performed &#8220;It&#8217;s All Over Now&#8221; in concert properly&#8211;and even then, it was a team-up. Bruce almost never cedes the vocal spotlight to one of his band members, but that night he shared the spotlight with Soozie for a reprise of their Stone Pony performance five years earlier.</p>\n<p>This time their performance was a true duet in a country swing arrangement, one of the highlights of a fun and unpredictable evening. (Bruce was apparently feeling magnanimous that night&#8211;Max also got a turn at lead vocals on &#8220;Boys.&#8221;)</p>\n<audio class=\"wp-audio-shortcode\" id=\"audio-29190-10\" preload=\"none\" style=\"width: 100%;\" controls=\"controls\"><source type=\"audio/mpeg\" src=\"https://estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/D1t11-its-all-over-now.mp3?_=10\" /><a href=\"https://estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/D1t11-its-all-over-now.mp3\">https://estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/D1t11-its-all-over-now.mp3</a></audio>\n<p>That duet was the last time &#8220;It&#8217;s All Over Now&#8221; has appeared on a Springsteen set list to date, but since it has a habit of popping up in the strangest of places and circumstances, it&#8217;ll almost certainly surface again someday. Let&#8217;s just hope someone captures it when it does.</p>\n<p><strong>It&#8217;s All Over Now<br />\nFirst performed:</strong> November 6, 1983 (Asbury Park, NJ)<br />\n<strong>Last performed:</strong> August 24, 2008 (Kansas City, MO)</p>\n<p>\u00a9 September 2, 2021</p>\n", "protected": false}, "excerpt": {"rendered": "<p>The Rolling Stones&#8217; first #1 U.K. hit had a habit of turning up in Bruce&#8217;s set lists in the strangest places, but fortunately a couple of his team-ups were captured for posterity.</p>\n", "protected": false}, "author": 1, "featured_media": 29244, "comment_status": "open", "ping_status": "open", "sticky": false, "template": "", "format": "standard", "meta": {"_monsterinsights_skip_tracking": false, "_monsterinsights_sitenote_active": false, "_monsterinsights_sitenote_note": "", "_monsterinsights_sitenote_category": 0, "_jetpack_newsletter_access": "", "_jetpack_dont_email_post_to_subs": false, "_jetpack_newsletter_tier_id": 0, "_jetpack_memberships_contains_paywalled_content": false, "_jetpack_feature_clip_id": 0, "_jetpack_memberships_contains_paid_content": false, "footnotes": "", "jetpack_publicize_message": "", "jetpack_publicize_feature_enabled": true, "jetpack_social_post_already_shared": true, "jetpack_social_options": {"image_generator_settings": {"template": "highway", "default_image_id": 0, "font": "", "enabled": false}, "version": 2}, "jetpack_post_was_ever_published": false}, "categories": [4, 3617, 5], "tags": [194, 839, 2433, 3270], "class_list": ["post-29190", "post", "type-post", "status-publish", "format-standard", "has-post-thumbnail", "hentry", "category-cover-me", "category-it-takes-two", "category-meeting-across-the-river", "tag-nils-lofgren", "tag-soozie-tyrell", "tag-the-rolling-stones", "tag-the-valentinos"], "aioseo_notices": [], "jetpack_publicize_connections": [], "jetpack_featured_media_url": "https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/stones.jpg?fit=1013%2C1024&ssl=1", "jetpack_sharing_enabled": true, "jetpack_shortlink": "https://wp.me/p9w3Lk-7AO", "jetpack_likes_enabled": true, "jetpack-relat